<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920109-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>920109-0063.</DOCID><HL>   Potlatch, Simpson   Unit Settle Civil Suit   Charging Pollution</HL><DATE>01/09/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   PCH</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)FOREST PRODUCTS, PRODUCERS OF WOOD AND LUMBER (FOR)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- Potlatch Corp. and Simpson Paper Co.entered into a consent decree and agreed to pay finestotaling $12 million to settle a civil suit chargingpollution of coastal waters near Los Angeles.   The lawsuit, filed in 1990 by the National Oceanic andAtmospheric Administration and by California, alleged thatthe discharge of chemicals such as polychlorinated biphenylsby the forest products companies and other corporations haddamaged marine resources off the Southern California shore.</LP><TEXT>   Potlatch operated a paper mill in Pomona, Calif., from1952 to 1979, when it was sold to San Francisco's SimpsonPaper Co., a unit of Simpson Investment Co., Seattle. Themill, which recycled waste paper, was alleged to be a sourceof PCBs.   Under the consent decree, which is subject to courtapproval, Potlatch will pay $9.5 million and Simpson will pay$2.5 million over four years. Potlatch said it has brought anaction for declaratory relief to recover the settlementamount from its insurance carriers.</TEXT></DOC>